'''Jerry M. Reinsdorf''' (born [[February 25]] [[1936]]) is a [[Certified Public Accountant|C.P.A.]], lawyer, and the majority owner of both the [[Chicago White Sox]] and the [[Chicago Bulls]].  He started his professional life as a tax attorney with the [[Internal Revenue Service]].  He has been the head of the White Sox and Bulls for over 20 years.  He made his initial fortune in [[real estate]] taking advantage of the [[Frank Lyon Co. v. United States]] decision in the [[United States Supreme Court]] which allowed economic owners of realty to sell property and lease it back while transferring the tax deduction for depreciation to the title owner.  He has become a sports owner with a reputation for frugality.

As the owner and Chairman of the Chicago Bulls since 1985, he has turned the franchise into a lucrative business that won six [[NBA Finals|World Championships]] in the 1990s (1991&ndash;1993 and 1996&ndash;1998). He is controversial for his involvement (along with [[Jerry Krause]]) in breaking up the championship team by not hiring back key personel such as [[Phil Jackson]] and [[Michael Jordan]].  He hired Jordan as a baseball player during his sabbatical from basketball.  He also moved the Bulls from [[Chicago Stadium]] to the [[United Center]].

As a baseball owner since 1981, he has brought success to the White Sox franchise.  The franchise made the playoffs in 1983 for the first time since 1959 and won the [[World Series]] in 2005 for the first time since 1917.  He moved the White Sox from [[Comiskey Park]] to [[New Comiskey Park]] and then renaming the new park U.S. Cellular Field. In both sporting endeavors, he has developed a reputation as an anti-labor union hardliner.  Since the early 1990s, he has been considered one of the most, if not the most, influential baseball owners.  He has been influential in instituting the [[salary cap]] and [[revenue sharing]].  He has also shaped the modern era of baseball by organizing the lucrative [[internet]] arm of baseball.

==Background==
Reinsdorf was born and raised in {{city-state|Brooklyn|New York}}.<ref name="JRC">{{cite web|url=http://chicago.whitesox.mlb.com/cws/team/exe_bios/reinsdorf_jerry.html|title=Jerry Reinsdorf, Chairman|accessdate=2008-10-08|publisher=[[MLB.com]]}}</ref>  He attended [[Erasmus Hall High School]] in Brooklyn,<ref>[http://www.nypost.com/seven/12312006/sports/the_rumble_sports_.htm?page=3 "The Rumble: AN OFF-THE-BALL LOOK AT YOUR FAVORITE SPORTS CELEBRITIES"], ''[[New York Post]]'', [[December 31]], [[2006]]. Accessed [[December 13]], [[2007]]. "The five Erasmus Hall of Fame legends include Raiders owner Al Davis, Bears quarterback Sid Luckman, Yankee pitching great Waite Hoyt, Billy Cunningham and Knicks founder Ned Irish. Other sports notables include Bulls/White Sox owner Jerry Reinsdorf, chess champion Bobby Fischer, ex-Browns head coach Sam Rutigliano, legendary NBA referee Norm Drucker and "Boys of Summer" author Roger Kahn."</ref> and he was the son of a [[sewing machine]] salesman.<ref name="TT#IS" /> A life-long baseball fan who grew up in the shadows of [[Ebbets Field]],<ref name=PH>{{cite web|url=http://www.cigaraficionado.com/Cigar/CA_Profiles/People_Profile/0,2540,87,00.html|title=Playing Hardball: Jerry Reinsdorf Got Michael Jordan Back Playing Basketball, But the Federal Courts Stymied His Assault on Baseball's Economics|accessdate=2008-10-26|date=2008|publisher=[[CigarAficionado.com]]|author=Kiersh, Edward}}</ref>  Reinsdorf was in the stands the day [[Jackie Robinson]] debuted for the Brooklyn Dodgers, breaking the color barrier which prevented black players from serving on Major League teams.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20080329&content_id=2464665&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb|title=Robinson, Reinsdorf honored on Friday: Hall of Famer, owner presented with Beacon Awards|accessdate=2008-10-26|date=2008-03-29|publisher=MLB Advanced Media, L.P|author=Bloom, Barry M.}}</ref>

Reinsdorf earned a [[bachelor's degree]] from [[George Washington University]] in {{city-state|Washington|District of Columbia}}.<ref name="CotCBJR">{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/bulls/news/jerry_reinsdorf.html|title= Chairman of the Chicago Bulls: Jerry Reinsdorf|accessdate=2008-10-07|publisher=NBA Media Ventures, LLC}}</ref>  He subsequently moved to Chicago in 1957.<ref name="CotCBJR" /> Reinsdorf became a C.P.A. and lawyer as well as a registered mortgage [[underwriter]] and a certified review [[appraiser]].<ref name="CotCBJR" /><ref name="FHTBT">{{cite web|url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,985640,00.html|title=For Him The Belle Toils|accessdate=2008-10-05|date=1996-12-02|publisher=[[Time Inc.]]|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|author=Wulf, Steve}}</ref>  He leveraged a full scholarship offer from the [[University of Chicago Law School]] into a scholarship from the [[Northwestern University School of Law]].<ref name=PH/>  His first job after graduating from Northwestern in 1960 was a [[delinquency]] case of [[Bill Veeck]] who at the time owned the White Sox.<ref name="TT#IS" /> In 1964, Reinsdorf went into private practice.  He developed a specialty in real estate partnership [[tax shelter]]s.  He sold his business interests in the real estate partnership in 1973 and formed Balcor, which raised [[US$]]650 million to invest in buildings under construction.  He sold Balcor in 1982 for $102 million to Shearson Lehman Brothers, the investment banking and brokerage arm of [[American Express]].<ref name="TT#IS" />  However, he continued to be President of the company for several years thereafter.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CTRB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0FF6300AB0002B2E&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=aa98cdc331574f0abeaff732b33dc0b2|title=Ex-Playboy Executive Named to Balcor Helm|accessdate=2008-10-08|date=1985-01-16|publisher=Newsbank|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=Ibata, David}}</ref>

==Sports ownership==
===New purchases===
In 1981 he was wealthy enough to purchase the White Sox for $19 million.<ref name="TT#IS" />  The purchase was brokered by [[American National Bank]] who arranged for a [[limited partnership]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.businessweek.com/archives/2000/b3697109.arc.htm|title=Bank, Bank, Bank for the Home Team: Lending to a big-league club pays off&mdash;and there are perks|accessdate=2008-10-07|date=2000-09-04|publisher=[[The McGraw-Hill Companies Inc.]]|work=[[BusinessWeek]]|author=Timmons, Heather}}</ref>  He follows previous eccentric White Sox owners [[Charles Comiskey]], who was known as a miser, and Veeck, who was known as a prankster who gutted the team by trading away promising prospects.<ref name="ASS">{{cite web|url=http://www.forbes.com/business/2005/10/27/baseball-sports-chicago-cz_mo_1027whitesox.html|title=A Sweet Sweep|accessdate=2008-10-07|date=2005-10-27|publisher= Forbes.com LLC.|work=[[Forbes]]|author=Ozanian, Michael K.}}</ref><ref name="WS">{{cite web|url=http://www.encyclopedia.chicagohistory.org/pages/276.html|title=White Sox|accessdate=2008-10-07|date=2005|publisher=[[Chicago Historical Society]]|work=The Electronic Encyclopedia of Chicago|author=Oshinsky, David M.}}</ref> Soon after buying the White Sox, he signed [[Greg Luzinski]] and [[Carlton Fisk]].  He also tripled the team promotional budget and increased the number of team [[scout (sports)|scouts]] from 12 to 20.  By the [[1983 Major League Baseball season]] the White Sox made the playoffs with the best record in the Major Leagues.<ref name="TT#IS" /><ref name="WS" />  The team initially signed a television deal with the newly founded [[Sportsvision]] under the new leadership of Chairman Reinsdorf and Vice Chairman [[Eddie Einhorn]], but that arrangement quickly fizzled.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.forbes.com/business/forbes/2002/0930/400096.html|title=A Long Strange Trip|accessdate=2008-10-07|date=2002-09-30|publisher= Forbes.com LLC.|work=[[Forbes]]|author=Armstrong, David}}</ref> Einhorn continues to be Vice Chairman of the White Sox.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.forbes.com/facesinthenews/2005/10/27/mclane-astros-baseball-cx_cn_1027autofacescan02.html|title=McLane's Astros Whitewashed By Chicago|accessdate=2008-10-07|date=2005-10-27|publisher= Forbes.com LLC.|work=[[Forbes]]|author=Noon, Chris}}</ref>

In 1985, following in the footsteps of Einhorn who had purchase a [[United States Football League]] franchise in 1984,<ref name="RNTBB" /> he purchased the Chicago Bulls as part of a [[syndicate]] for US$16 million and quickly turned the team from one that averaged 6,365 fans per game at the 17,339-seat [[Chicago Stadium]] in 1985 into one with an 8,000-person [[season ticket]] waiting list.<ref name="TT#IS" />  He did so by drafting [[Horace Grant]] and [[Scottie Pippen]], and trading for [[Bill Cartwright]] to join [[John Paxson]] and Michael Jordan under the tutelage of [[head coach]] [[Doug Collins]].  In 1989, the team signed [[Phil Jackson]] as the final piece of the championship puzzle.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.encyclopedia.chicagohistory.org/pages/184.html|title=Bulls|accessdate=2008-10-07|date=2005|publisher=[[Chicago Historical Society]]|work=The Electronic Encyclopedia of Chicago|author=Isaacson, Melissa}}</ref>  From November 20, 1987 through Jordan's 1999 retirement the Bulls sold out every game.<ref name="YMTaH" /> 

In the months prior to the purchase, [[Milwaukee]] businessman [[Marvin Fishman]] had been awarded a $16.2 million judgment against the Bulls.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CTRB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0FF6304B79B56ABE&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=aa98cdc331574f0abeaff732b33dc0b2|title=Sports|accessdate=2008-10-08|date=1985-01-24|publisher=Newsbank|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=Myslenski, Skip, and Linda Kay}}</ref>  Fishman had been illegally blocked from purchasing the team in 1972.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CTRB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0FF630C681123A90&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=aa98cdc331574f0abeaff732b33dc0b2|title=Reinsdorf Buys Bulls|accessdate=2008-10-08|date=1985-02-09|publisher=Newsbank|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=Sakamoto, Bob}}</ref>  Reinsdorf purchased the team from an ownership group that included [[Lamar Hunt]], [[George Steinbrenner]], [[Walter Shorenstein]], [[Jonathan Kovler]], [[Lester Crown]], [[Philip Klutznick]], and the estate of [[Arthur Wirtz]],<ref name="RNTBB">{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CTRB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0FF6303C4017BF7E&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=aa98cdc331574f0abeaff732b33dc0b2|title=Reinsdorf Negotiating To Buy Bulls|accessdate=2008-10-08|date=1985-01-22|publisher=Newsbank|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=Sakamoto, Bob}}</ref> and he held a $9.2 million controlling interest in the team.<ref name="YMTaH">{{cite web|url=http://www.businessweek.com/archives/1999/b3613101.arc.htm|title=Yikes! Mike Takes a Hike: How Jordan's exit is shaking the world of sports business|accessdate=2008-10-07|date=1999-01-25|publisher=[[The McGraw-Hill Companies Inc.]]|work=[[BusinessWeek]]|author=Crockett, Roger O. et al.}}</ref>  Reinsdorf's share of 56.8% of the team was purchased from Klutznick, Steinbrenner, Shorenstein and the estate of Wirtz.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CTRB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0FF630C68FCC7196&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=aa98cdc331574f0abeaff732b33dc0b2|title=Reinsdorf Shows He's All Business|accessdate=2008-10-08|date=1985-02-09|publisher=Newsbank|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=Daley, Steven}}</ref>  His purchase ended an era in which the Bulls were managed by committee with decisions by conference call, verdicts by vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CTRB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0FF630D1AEA88F2E&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=aa98cdc331574f0abeaff732b33dc0b2|title=Reinsdorf Tackles Bulls By The Horns|accessdate=2008-10-08|date=1985-02-10|publisher=Newsbank|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=Verdi, Bob}}</ref>  Reinsdorf acquired his majority interests on March 11, 1985 and that same week Kovler sold his 7% stake in the team, bringing Reinsdorf's interest to 63%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CTRB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0FF63253B42C756E&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=aa98cdc331574f0abeaff732b33dc0b2|title=Defenseless Bulls Ripped By Bullets|accessdate=2008-10-08|date=1985-03-12|publisher=Newsbank|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=Sakamoto, Bob}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CTRB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0FF6326511E8617A&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=aa98cdc331574f0abeaff732b33dc0b2|title=Kovler Bows Out As a Bull's Owner|accessdate=2008-10-08|date=1985-03-13|publisher=Newsbank|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=Sakamoto, Bob}}</ref>  The following week Reinsdorf ousted [[Rod Thorn]] as [[general manager]] and replaced him with [[Jerry Krause]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CTRB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0FF633A90D1A95E8&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=aa98cdc331574f0abeaff732b33dc0b2|title=Thorn is Out As Bulls' GM|accessdate=2008-10-08|date=1985-03-26|publisher=Newsbank|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=Sakamoto, Bob}}</ref>

===Ownership history===
{{Quote box
 | quote  = "The North Siders always tended to look down on [[South Side (Chicago)|South Siders]]. . .Part of being a White Sox fan is you hate the [[Chicago Cubs|Cubs]]."
 | source = <U+2014>[[Jerry Reinsdorf]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newsweek.com/id/127762|title=Acting Frisky At Comiskey: The Stodgy Old White Sox Are Suddenly Hipsters|accessdate=2008-10-06|date=1990-07-09|publisher=Newsweek, Inc.|work=[[Newsweek]]|author=Barrett, Todd}}</ref>
 | width  = 15%
 | align  = right
}}
The White Sox have won [[American League]] regular season Division Championships in 1983, 1993, 2000, 2005 and 2008 under Reinsdorf and they won the [[2005 World Series]].<ref name="JRC" />  In addition, they were in first place at the conclusion of the strike-shortened [[1994 Major League Baseball season]].<ref name="JRC" />  The World Series victory made him only the third owner in the history of North American sports to win a championship in two different sports. The baseball championship boosted the value of the franchise to over $300 million.<ref name="ASS" />  When Reinsdorf signed Jordan after Jordan's announcement that he wanted to play baseball, many thought Jordan's drawing power provided an ulterior motive.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,982688,00.html|title=More Air Goes Out of Baseball|accessdate=2008-10-05|date=1995-03-20|publisher=[[Time Inc.]]|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|author=Wulf, Steve}}</ref>  Reinsdorf, however, had tried to convince Jordan not to give up basketball,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newsweek.com/id/122911|title=I Have Nothing Left To Prove: There Was Only One More Thing For Michael Jordan To Do With A Basketball: Put It Down And Walk Away. This Is How He Reached His Decision.|accessdate=2008-10-06|date=1993-10-18|publisher=Newsweek, Inc.|work=[[Newsweek]]|author=Starr, Mark}}</ref> but he did not attempt to make Jordan the highest paid player in the game like some feel he should have.<ref name="HD" />

As a basketball owner, he has been described by ''[[Time]]'' as a "cheapskate",<ref name="TOAO">{{cite web|url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,988581,00.html|title=The One And Only|accessdate=2008-10-05|date=1998-06-22|publisher=[[Time Inc.]]|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|author=Stein, Joel, Julie Grace, John U. Bacon, and Sally B. Donnelly}}</ref> a reference they also use for his baseball persona.<ref name="EYaM">{{cite web|url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,1122011,00.html|title=Every Year, a Miracle|accessdate=2008-10-05|date=2005-10-23|publisher=[[Time Inc.]]|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|author=Thigpen, David}}</ref>  As of 1995, the time when [[Scottie Pippen]] was eager to either be traded or be rid of Krause, he had never renegotiated a contract.<ref name="HD" />  As a baseball owner, he has had a reputation as one of the most militant, anti-union, hard-line owners.<ref name="FHTBT" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,975797-2,00.html|title=A Whole New Ball Game|accessdate=2008-10-05|date=1992-06-22|publisher=[[Time Inc.]]|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|author=McCarroll, Thomas}}</ref><ref name="AOWWPBWTOB">{{cite web|url=http://www.newsweek.com/id/109955|title=An Owner Who Won't Play Ball With The Other Boys: Sports: As Spring Training Starts With Replacement Players, Angelos Of The Orioles Just Says No|accessdate=2008-10-06|date=1995-03-13|publisher=Newsweek, Inc.|work=[[Newsweek]]|author=Starr, Mark}}</ref>  ''[[Newsweek]]'' described him as "one of the hardest heads in the [[1994 Major League Baseball strike|1994 baseball strike]]".<ref name="HD">{{cite web|url=http://www.newsweek.com/id/110006|title=Hoop Dreams: The Worlds Greatest Basketball Player Walked Away From The Game Eighteen Months Ago. Will Michael Jordan Take To The Air Once Again?|accessdate=2008-10-06|date=1995-03-20|publisher=Newsweek, Inc.|work=[[Newsweek]]}}</ref> In the baseball offseason between the [[1992 Major League Baseball season|1992]] and [[1993 Major League Baseball season|1993]] seasons, he completely abstained from the [[free agent]] market.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.businessweek.com/archives/1993/b331447.arc.htm|title=BASEBALL'S OWNERS ARE FINALLY TAKING A WHACK AT THE BALL |accessdate=2008-10-07|date=1993-04-12|publisher=[[The McGraw-Hill Companies Inc.]]|work=[[BusinessWeek]]|author=Greising, David, Gail DeGeorge, Bob Andelman, and Harris Collingwood}}</ref>  Reinsdorf was one of the last holdouts to the 1996 labor agreement that instituted the [[salary cap]] while retaining [[arbitration]] rights for the players.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.businessweek.com/archives/1996/b3490065.arc.htm|title=THIS RELIEF PITCHER MAY GET THE SAVE |accessdate=2008-10-07|date=1996-08-26|publisher=[[The McGraw-Hill Companies Inc.]]|work=[[BusinessWeek]]|author=Greising, David|editor=Holland, Kelley}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.businessweek.com/archives/1994/b339449.arc.htm|title=SPORTS SALARY CAPS: ONE SIZE FITS NOBODY |accessdate=2008-10-07|date=1994-10-17|publisher=[[The McGraw-Hill Companies Inc.]]|work=[[BusinessWeek]]|author=Greising, David}}</ref>  His 1996 signing of [[Albert Belle]] made news because of his widely-publicized general opposition to spiraling player salaries.<ref name="FHTBT" /> The $55 million signing was a turning point in the decision by the baseball owners to agree to [[revenue sharing]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.businessweek.com/archives/1996/b3506104.arc.htm|title=COMMENTARY: BASEBALL'S LOSERS STILL LOSE|accessdate=2008-10-07|date=1996-12-16|publisher=[[The McGraw-Hill Companies Inc.]]|work=[[BusinessWeek]]|author=Baker, Stephen}}</ref> The signing also made Reinsdorf the employer of the highest paid [[Major League Baseball]] player and highest paid professional basketball player (Jordan) at the same time.<ref name="FHTBT" />  Reinsdorf had just re-signed Jordan after the [[1995&ndash;96 NBA season]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newsweek.com/id/101470|title=Raging Bulls: Magic Filled The Headlines, But Michael Was Making History. Can His Brilliant Team Maintain Its Record Pace? |accessdate=2008-10-06|date=1996-02-12|publisher=Newsweek, Inc.|work=[[Newsweek]]}}</ref> However, Jordan had been underpaid most of his career,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newsweek.com/id/108041|title=Let Him Walk!!!: Just Kidding&mdash;Sort Of Michael Jordan Is The Greatest Player Ever. But Is He Worth The Big Bucks He Wants?|accessdate=2008-10-07|date=1996-07-01|publisher=Newsweek, Inc.|work=[[Newsweek]]|author=Rhodes, Steve and Larry Reibstein}}</ref> and Reinsdorf, who did not feel he could justify the $30 million salary from a business standpoint,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.businessweek.com/archives/1996/b3486051.arc.htm|title=RUN, JUMP&mdash;AND SELL: Commercial exploitation of sports explodes|accessdate=2008-10-07|date=1996-07-29|publisher=[[The McGraw-Hill Companies Inc.]]|work=[[BusinessWeek]]}}</ref> immediately realized he was going to soon feel [[buyer's remorse]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newsweek.com/id/94365|title=Race, Respect And The Nba: Conflicts Over Money And Control Have Kept The Lockout Going. But There's Been Another X-Factor: The Divide Between White Owners And Black |accessdate=2008-10-07|date=1998-12-21|publisher=Newsweek, Inc.|work=[[Newsweek]]|author=Samuels, Allison}}</ref> Even his most successful baseball team was not highly paid: when the White Sox won the [[2005 World Series]], Reinsdorf had the 13th highest payroll of the 30 Major League Baseball teams.<ref name="EYaM" />  

After Reinsdorf purchased the team in 1981, the team experienced erosion of fan and media support which led to of moving the team.<ref name="WS" />  He complained about old [[Comiskey Park]] with its foible such as numerous obstructed view seats and threatened to move the White Sox.<ref name="CP">{{cite web|url=http://www.encyclopedia.chicagohistory.org/pages/315.html|title=Comiskey Park|accessdate=2008-10-07|date=2005|publisher=[[Chicago Historical Society]]|work=The Electronic Encyclopedia of Chicago|author=Bachin, Robin F.}}</ref> Among his threats was moving the team to [[Itasca, IL|Itasca]] or {{city-state|Addison|Illinois}} in [[DuPage County, IL|DuPage County]].<ref name="CP" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CTRB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0FF6305FD6C10F21&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=aa98cdc331574f0abeaff732b33dc0b2|title=A Superstadium?|accessdate=2008-10-08|date=1985-01-27|publisher=Newsbank|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=Sneed, Michael, and Cheryl Lavin}}</ref>  Reinsdorf, through his real estate business purchased {{convert|100|acre|m2|lk=on}} in Addison.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CTRB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0FF63133F0D3BE2A&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=aa98cdc331574f0abeaff732b33dc0b2|title=Sox Owner's Firm Buys Du Page Site|accessdate=2008-10-08|date=1985-02-22|publisher=Newsbank|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=Schmeltzer, John}}</ref> [[Chicago Mayor]] [[Harold Washington]] lobbied the [[Illinois Legislature]],<ref name="CP" /> and subsequently then-[[Illinois Governor]] [[James R. Thompson]] promoted a package of incentives to retain the team in Chicago. The state floated bonds to build [[New Comiskey Park]] and let Reinsdorf keep all parking and concession revenues, as well as the $5 million per year from 89 skyboxes.<ref name="TT#IS" />  Reinsdorf and [[Chicago Blackhawks]] owner, [[Bill Wirtz|William Wirtz]] contributed $175 million to fund the construction of the largest arena in the United States.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.encyclopedia.chicagohistory.org/pages/1285.html|title=United Center|accessdate=2008-10-07|date=2005|publisher=[[Chicago Historical Society]]|work=The Electronic Encyclopedia of Chicago|author=Greene, Daniel}}</ref>  When the [[United Center]] opened in 1994 all of the skyboxes were leased for up to eight years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.businessweek.com/archives/1993/b334139.arc.htm|title=THE NBA MAY FEEL A VOID--BUT JORDAN INC. WILL PLAY ON|accessdate=2008-10-07|date=1993-10-18|publisher=[[The McGraw-Hill Companies Inc.]]|work=[[BusinessWeek]]|author=Greising, David, Dori Jones Yang, and Laura Zinn}}</ref>  As per the [[collective bargaining agreement]], Reinsdorf was allowed to exclude 60% of luxury suite revenue from "basketball-related income" and thus it is not part of the revenue sharing income.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.forbes.com//forbes/1998/1214/6213124a.html|title=Selective accounting|accessdate=2008-10-07|date=1998-12-14|publisher= Forbes.com LLC.|work=[[Forbes]]|author=Ozanian, Michael K.}}</ref>

